<HEADLINE>
FT  24 JAN 92 / Survey of FT Quarterly Review of Personal Finance (2): A
real top rate of 59% - If Labour wins . . . / There are limits to what the
Opposition can divulge, but savers should ignore the cries of salesmen
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN AUTHERS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
SPARE A thought for the Opposition.
The Labour party is under pressure to provide details of exactly what tax
rates it would impose throughout the next government. The faintest
obfuscation is punished in the press.
Meanwhile, Norman Lamont, the chancellor, is in purdah. He is not allowed to
comment, even vaguely, about changes to come in the budget that is less than
two months away.
Bear this in mind when looking at Labour's proposals. There are limits to
what it can be expected to divulge, and also on what it can commit itself to
at this stage.
The broad principles are clear. According to Margaret Beckett, the shadow
treasury minister: 'We are looking for a greater degree of equity. We want
the tax system to treat everyone fairly, but we think people on the highest
earnings can afford to pay more at the top end.'
This in itself limits the financial plans that people should make in
preparing for a Labour government - while another problem with forward
planning, of course, is that Labour may not win the coming general election.
The broader issues of macro-economics are likely to be more important than
alterations to the tax system. However, there are few moves that savers and
investors can make to protect themselves against the chance of a Labour
government which do not make sense anyway. For this reason, it is best to
ignore some of the more desperate 'buy now while stocks last' pleas, which
may come from salesmen and advisers.
What follows is a summary of Labour's current thinking.
The first budget
Income tax: The top rate would rise from 40 per cent to 50 per cent. This is
a firm pledge. Mrs Beckett suggests that this will go no higher: 'While 50
per cent is fair at the top end, it is enough.' The threshold for this top
band would be around Pounds 40,000. Below this, people would continue to pay
40 per cent.
However, the upper limit for national insurance contributions would be
phased out. In the current regime, contributions are only paid, at the rate
of 9 per cent, on the first Pounds 18,200 of earned income. Abolishing the
threshold would mean that the top rate of tax effectively became 59 per
cent.
Income tax for those in lower tax brackets should eventually come down to
below 25 per cent, though Labour now makes it quite clear that this would be
unlikely in the first budget.
Married couples' tax allowance: This will be frozen. Note that it will be
left to 'wither on the vine' - with inflation gradually reducing the value
of the benefit.
Investment income. This would be surcharged. Labour wants to make unearned
income subject to national insurance contributions at the same rate (9 per
cent) as earned income. The idea is to put earned and unearned income on a
'level playing field'.
Thresholds would be high - an income of Pounds 3,000 from investment would
probably be needed before you paid any tax on it. Thus, this measure would
be unlikely to affect those with less than Pounds 30,000 in savings. People
above the state retirement age would be exempt. Income from pensions paid to
people who retire before this age is also exempt, but any other investment
income they derive would be liable to this charge.
However, this measure has still caused more concern than any other Labour
proposal. It discourages saving. There is also the argument that so-called
'unearned' income usually derives from money saved out of earned income.
Mrs Beckett defends the proposal against these charges, saying that it
equalises the taxation of earned and unearned income. 'It may be the case
that it's income they've earned over a lifetime, but it may be income that
they have not worked for at all. We don't think it's unfair to treat the
same level of income as subject to the same level of charge.'
She cites accountants who say that their clients do better by living off
their investments, rather than going out and earning money. However, the
move still removes an incentive to save for people between middle age and
retirement.
Tessas: Tax-exempt special saver accounts seem likely to stay. Labour
welcomes them as having 'one small part' to play in increasing saving, and
dampening demand, but suspects that they are not encouraging much new
saving.
Pensions: State pensions will be increased by Pounds 5 a week for single
pensioners and Pounds 8 a week for married couples, over and above the rate
of inflation.
Labour would reinvigorate the State Earnings-related Pensions Scheme (Serps)
by relating it to earnings over the 20 best years of the user's career,
rather than the average of the whole of it.
Any new personal pension plans would have to guarantee a return of at least
the amount to be gained via the new Serps.
Business Expansion Scheme: The BES for private 'assured tenancies' would be
ended, possibly in the first budget. Labour is highly critical of the scheme
as it works at present. But a scheme similar to the original Business
Start-up Scheme might well be established, with big incentives to invest in
small firms and manufacturing.
The long-term plans
Tax avoidance: Loopholes will be plugged, probably by a system modelled on
the US, where those on high income have to pay a minimum proportion of that
income in tax, regardless of any other allowances and reliefs.
Labour would set a maximum level of allowances for people above a certain
income. This could substantially choke off the appeal of 'tax shelter'
investments, such as enterprise-zone property.
Capital gains tax: The threshold will probably come down from the present
Pounds 5,500, but stay above the level of income tax allowances. Mrs Beckett
categorically denies that the Pounds 1,000 figure bandied about in the press
has any basis in fact - the threshold will stay much higher than this.
One scheme in favour with researchers would cut the level of tax according
to how long an investment had been held before sale. Stags involved in
short-term speculation would pay heavy amounts of tax, while patient holders
of shares for 10 years or more would pay virtually nothing. Clearly, this
scheme could be complicated, but if it could be made to work it would be a
powerful and direct incentive for long-termism.
Inheritance tax: A 'more effective and progressive form of taxation' than
IHT would be introduced, to tax wealth. Tax would be payable on gifts as
well as legacies, so the new tax would resemble capital transfer tax. IHT
would also, probably, be based on the recipient, encouraging wider dispersal
of wealth. This makes comparisons of thresholds and rates awkward.
On a recipient basis, the threshold would probably be a lot lower than the
current Pounds 140,000. However, it would allow people to avoid tax being
paid on their estate altogether, if they spread their money among enough
people in their wills. Another possible measure is to tax transfers between
individuals on a lifetime basis, rather than annually.
Labour dissents strongly from the suggestion, signalled by the
Conservatives, that the next budget should actually make IHT more lenient by
increasing the threshold.
Personal equity plans: Labour will honour existing tax commitments on all
existing plans. Beyond that, the party is examining Peps, and is now less
negative about them than it was. Complete abolition is still an option, but
Labour is interested in using the Pep concept to encourage investment in
manufacturing industries.
Sectors to watch if Labour wins, Page 13
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page IV Photograph Winning smiles? If so, the broad principles are
clear, people on the highest earnings can afford to pay more tax, says
Margaret Beckett (Omitted).
</PAGE>
