<HEADLINE>
FT  24 JAN 92 / World Stock Markets: Retailing trio enliven trading in
Brussels - Optimistic company announcements have attracted the investors
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW HILL
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE Belgian bourse has only recently shaken off the depressing effect of
last November's inconclusive general election. After falling to around 1,060
in December, the Bel20 has since recovered, closing at 1,183.63 yesterday.
But confusion over the shape of the next government has not stopped the
Belgians shopping. Recent weeks have seen increased activity in the Belgian
retailing sector, which accounts for about 5 or 6 per cent of the entire
market. Shares in the three principal distribution companies  - GIB Group,
Delhaize 'Le Lion' and Colruyt - have all shown strong increases over the
last month, in spite of some profit-taking in the last week.
This is not a new or short-lived phenomenon. Colruyt and Delhaize have
improved relative to the rest of the bourse during the last year, while GIB
has managed only a marginal outperformance. 'They are always among the most
active stocks,' points out one Brussels analyst. By the middle of January,
Colruyt, the smallest of the trio, had outperformed the lacklustre Belgian
market by 65 per cent on a yearly basis though it has since slipped back to
just over 50 per cent.
Belgium's quoted retailers are founded on the supermarket business. For
example, although GIB also owns fast-food restaurants, department stores and
do-it-yourself outlets (including a strong US presence), some 65 per cent of
its BFr205bn (Dollars 6.3bn) turnover in 1990 came from supermarkets and
hypermarkets.
Recent enthusiasm for the retailers seems to have been spurred by a number
of optimistic company announcements. Delhaize - largest of the three - said
on January 10 that it was expecting to record a 14 per cent increase in
consolidated net profit for 1991, on the back of a 16.4 per cent rise in
sales to BFr310bn (Dollars 9.5bn). The principal motor for this growth was
the company's Food Lion supermarket chain in the US, which pushed up its
sales by 15.3 per cent by opening more than 100 new stores last year. A
further 125 are expected to open in 1992.
In the same week, GIB announced that it was planning to invest BFr6.4bn
(Dollars 198m) during 1992 - up 21 per cent on last year - concentrating,
among other things, on the installation of electronic payment and scanning
systems in its supermarkets.
Colruyt, meanwhile, has been plugging away at the low-cost, no-frills end of
the Belgian retail market and paying back debt built up during the difficult
years of 1985 and 1986. It, too, has recently unveiled a handsome increase
in 1991 turnover - up 19 per cent to BFr34.3bn (Dollars 1.061bn).
Such virtues have attracted the attention of investors on both sides of the
Atlantic. Delhaize's share price in Brussels has risen partly on the back of
its trading performance, but also because of increased interest in Food
Lion, which is separately quoted in New York. In turning to Europe, say
analysts, US investors are shunning the depressed British retail market and
looking to fill their shopping trolleys with undervalued continental stocks.
Belgian retailing is still a relatively low-margin business, because of high
labour costs. Computerisation of store check-outs and the development of
own-brand products - both of which lag behind, say, British supermarket
groups - should lead to strong improvement in profitability in the coming
years.
In this way, the most sluggish of the Belgian trio, GIB, is also the most
interesting because it is only now pushing through the investments which
other retailers have carried out. '(Buyers of GIB stock) are betting on an
adjustment or improvement in the competition in the business,' says Mr
Thierry Masset, a retail analyst with Generale de Banque in Brussels.
Optimists say that this, in effect, is a one-way bet. Belgian planning law
makes it difficult for new groups to win permission to build large
supermarkets. 'The only way of getting into the market is to acquire another
company,' says one London-based retail analyst. If GIB falls behind with its
investment programme or does not develop quickly enough, he adds, then there
could well be plenty of frustrated buyers waiting to bid for the entire
group.
</TEXT>
