<HEADLINE>
FT  24 JAN 92 / International Equity Issues: France set to back down on
capital gains tax plan
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By TRACY CORRIGAN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE FRENCH Treasury is understood to be ready to back down over proposals
designed to tighten rules governing the taxation of capital gains earned by
French residents.
The proposals, as originally conceived, could have driven debt issuance by
French borrowers offshore and reduced the liquidity of the French bond
market.
Yesterday, Credit Foncier changed plans to launch a domestic issue with an
international tranche because of fears of the tax changes. Instead, the
financial institution launched a FFr3bn Eurobond and a FFr1.2bn domestic
bond issues.
In fact, the proposals were intended to facilitate taxation of capital gains
earned on 'stripped' bonds - bonds which have been reduced to their
component parts of individual coupons. But the proposals, in their initial
form, would also have affected the issuance of fungible debt held by French
investors.
French borrowers, in an effort to increase the liquidity of their debt,
frequently add new tranches to existing issues, a practice which would have
been penalised under the proposed changes.
The proposal would have scuppered the chances of France's burgeoning public
debt market, set up last month by four leading state-owned entities
including Credit Foncier. The market, designed to combine international and
domestic distribution, imitates the structure of the French Treasury market,
with a group of committed market-makers called Specialistes en Valeurs du
Secteur Public (SVP).
The change would also have gone against the French government's strong
tradition of promoting market reform and encouraging liquidity.
The Treasury is expected to back down following representations by the
French banks.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 25
</PAGE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>FT921-12853</DOCNO>
