<TEXT>
ABERFOYLE, the Tasman-ian-based mining group, has joined the list of
Australian resources companies which have fallen victim to historically low
world metal prices, writes Bruce Jacques in Sydney.
The base metals company has cut its annual dividend to 10 cents a share from
27.5 cents after 1991 earnings fell to ADollars 10.9m (Dollars 8.38m) from
ADollars 30.0m. Revenue fell to Dollars 125.6m from ADollars 179.1m. The
directors said the decline was caused by sharply lower metal prices and near
exhaustion of the company's long-standing Que River operation.
Yesterday's report indicated the Hellyer operation was the company's most
profitable.
