<HEADLINE>
FT  24 JAN 92 / International Company News: JCL to be liquidated with Y129bn
outstanding debts
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT THOMSON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   TOKYO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
JCL, a property and sales affiliate of Janome Sewing x Machine, one of the
world's leading sewing machine makers, began liquidation proceedings
yesterday with outstanding debts of Y129bn (Dollars 1.04bn), which arose
from Janome's dealings with a stock speculator group.
The collapse of JCL symbolises the sometimes disastrous results of
conservative Japanese manufacturing companies' diversification into property
development and their uncharacteristic links with stock speculators during
the financial frenzy of the late 1980s.
Janome was entangled in the failure early last year of Nanatomi, a property
and stock speculator which had outstanding debts of Y300bn and was then
Japan's third largest bankruptcy on record. Through JCL and another ailing
affiliate, New Home Credit, Janome had guaranteed loans of about Y187bn for
Nanatomi, and was left exposed after the company's collapse.
JCL had come to guarantee the money after a Nanatomi executive, Mr Masayuki
Yasuda, was appointed to the Janome board in 1989, and later became its
vice-president. While he claimed to have ended his days as a stock
speculator, Mr Yasuda later admitted to close links to Mr Mitsuhiro Kotani,
the head of the Koshin speculator group charged with attempting to extort
Y30bn from Janome.
Nanatomi and Koshin began buying Janome shares in late 1985, when the sewing
machine maker became one of many targets of the speculative buying that was
characteristic of the Tokyo market at that time.
At the start of 1986, Janome shares were at Y380, by March they reached
Y1,900 and in November they were trading at Y2,600.
The speculators' purchase of Janome shares was partly inspired by the belief
that the company's 180 fully-owned sales outlets in Japan were a potential
property goldmine, bearing in mind the then fast-rising price of land.
Meanwhile, Janome had hoped the loans to Nanatomi would ensure that the
speculators' holding, which reached almost 40 per cent, would not be
on-passed to another predator.
JCL was established in 1988 as part of Janome's plans to expand into
non-manufacturing business such as jewellery, restaurants and sports clubs.
The company, apparently in expectation of yesterday's filing with the Tokyo
District Court, had last year reduced its staff from 60 to five.
While JCL is to be liquidated, Janome has the backing of its main bank,
Kyowa Saitama Bank, which has already replaced several executives at the
sewing machine company and whose affiliates took control of 81 per cent of
JCL shares. The former president of Saitama Bank resigned last year to take
responsibility for its exposure to Janome before his bank merged with Kyowa
Bank.
Janome has announced that a large part of a Tokyo plant will sold to pay off
debts, while Kyowa Saitama has assured other creditors that it is supporting
the company. The sewing machine maker is reported to have sold some of its
cross-held shares in financial institutions to raise funds, including part
of its stake in Kyowa Saitama.
Other listed companies caught in the Nanatomi collapse, including Tobishima
Corporation, the construction company, are also being restructured with the
assistance of their main bank - in Tobishima's case, Fuji Bank.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
