<HEADLINE>
FT  24 JAN 92 / International Company News: Stratus to supply International
Computers
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALAN CANE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
STRATUS COMPUTER of the US has agreed to supply International Computers
(ICL), the UK-based company in which Fujitsu of Japan has a majority stake,
with fault-tolerant computers in a deal which underlines the interdependence
of computer manufacturers today.
Stratus, based in Marlboro, Massachusetts, also supplies its computers under
non-exclusive agreements to International Business Machines (IBM), the
world's largest computer manufacturer, which at one time comprised 30 per
cent of Stratus' market, Olivetti of Italy, Ericsson of Sweden, and NEC of
Japan.
The company turned over Dollars 448.6m in 1991, a rise of 11 per cent on the
preceding year, with earnings of Dollars 49.7m, up 23 per cent.
Fault-tolerant or continuous availability computers are designed so that
single faults will not stop the system functioning. They have become
essential for critical applications including money transfer and security
where malfunctioning computers cannot be tolerated. The worldwide market for
systems of this kind is estimated at Dollars 12bn.
The market leader is Tandem Computers of the US; other manufacturers
including Digital Equipment and Hewlett Packard now also offer
fault-tolerant systems.
Mr William Foster, president and chief executive officer, said Stratus and
ICL were complementary; ICL had special expertise in the Unix operating
system which was the fastest-growing area of the Stratus marketplace.
Mr David Berry, director of associated services at ICL, said he expected to
sell Pounds 10m (Dollars 18.1m) worth of Stratus hardware in the first year
of a five-year plan in which revenues should reach between Pounds 50m and
Pounds 100m.
Stratus and ICL sales forces would complement each other in the UK rather
than compete. ICL's chief aim in selling Stratus hardware would be to
strengthen its role in the financial services market as well as public
utilities, telecommunications and security.
ICL and Stratus have worked together informally since 1987; ICL installed
Stratus computers at Deutsche Press-Agentur, Germany's largest press agency.
</TEXT>
