<HEADLINE>
FT  24 JAN 92 / International Company News: News of charge wipes 8% off
Norsk Hydro shares
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By KAREN FOSSLI
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   OSLO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
NORSK HYDRO, Norway's biggest company, is to take a NKr2.4bn (Dollars 387m)
special charge against its 1991 fourth-quarter accounts. The announcement
wiped 8 per cent off the company's stock market capitalisation yesterday.
The charge will cover the costs of restructuring and asset write-downs
associated with the agriculture and magnesium divisions.
Norsk Hydro's shares plunged NKr12.50, nearly 8 per cent, to NKr144.50 on
the news.
The company said NKr1bn of the charge related to the agriculture division
and NKr1.4bn to the magnesium division. Of the total, some NKr800m will
cover costs for the restructuring, while around NKr1.6bn represents
write-downs.
For the first nine months of 1991, group net income was NKr1.04bn, down from
NKr1.89bn a year earlier. Agriculture had an operating profit of NKr433m, on
sales of NKr20.03bn, while light metals - which includes the magnesium
division - achieved an operating income of NKr460m on sales of NKr13.10bn.
One Oslo-based analyst forecast that the final-quarter charges would push
Hydro into a net loss of between NKr800m and NKr1bn for 1991. The results
are due to be published on February 20. Hydro made a net profit of NKr2.9bn
in 1990.
Norsk Hydro said a big part of the charge against the magnesium division
earnings represented a write-down of the book value of the plant in
Becancour, Canada.
Last October Hydro charged NKr500m in its third-quarter accounts to cover
costs associated with the restructuring of the agriculture and magnesium
divisions, which it said was meant to lead to annual cost reductions of
about NKr260m. Hydro said a strong deterioration of the magnesium market,
combined with increased exports from eastern Europe, created a need for
adjustments in marketing and production activities.
To this end, Hydro said plans for restructuring would be completed during
the first half of 1991. However, this would depend to a large extent on the
outcome of the US trade policy cases.
Hydro said although there was over-capacity in the European fertiliser
industry, demand was expected to grow outside Europe.
To contend with these market conditions, the company intends to reduce
European capacity.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
