<HEADLINE>
FT  24 JAN 92 / Letter: Casting doubt on Home Office 'surprise' over poll
tax issue
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   From Dr STEPHEN CASTELL
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Sir, With regard to the 'apparent loophole' in the law over the
admissibility of computerised records as evidence in civil proceedings in
magistrates' courts ('Poll tax dilemma that is a matter of records', January
18), I doubt that the Home Office has been 'taken by surprise'.
During 1987 and 1988 I carried out reviews of the position in English (and
to some extent, Scottish) law of admissibility of computer evidence in both
civil and criminal proceedings. These studies were commissioned by the
Central Computer and Telecommunications Agency. Copies of the final reports
were, I believe, submitted by the CCTA to the Treasury, the Home Office, the
Lord Chancellor's department and the Scottish Office.
Incidentally, I am not sure it is true that 'the government knows it could
easily close the loophole by parliamentary order'. Even if it were true,
however, it would not alter the inherent problem in the central issue here:
the need for computer systems and operational practices properly capable of
forensic scrutiny, delivering undoubted evidential reliability.
It is thus not just computerised poll tax records which are affected. The
report signposted similar potential difficulties arising in, for example,
the authentication of 'dematerialised' Taurus share certificates, and the
'phantom withdrawal' syndrome of ATM cash-dispensers.
Stephen Castell,
Castell,
20 Grange Road,
Wickham Bishops,
Witham, Essex CM8 3LT
</TEXT>
