<HEADLINE>
FT  24 JAN 92 / Arts: Today's Television
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER DUNKLEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
In the second of its three programmes about Billy Wilder, Arena (9.30 BBC2)
covers the making of various movies from Ace In The Hole to Sabrina.
Discussing Sunset Boulevard, Wilder explains that Mae West was the original
choice to play the ageing star of the silent movies, though Gloria Swanson
eventually got the part. At 12.05 BBC2 screens Sunset Boulevard itself, just
about the best Hollywood put-down ever made, matched only by Kenneth Anger's
weird book, Hollywood Babylon, in its readiness to concentrate on the warts
and forget the all. The script is wonderfully acid.
Channel 4 presents the first in another series (the fourth) of Whose Line Is
It Anyway? (10.35) one of the few really different ideas to have turned up
in television light entertainment in 25 years. Once again Clive Anderson
chairs the contest in which entertainers improvise before a studio audience.
Clashing head on with Sunset Boulevard at 12.05 is Monterey Pop (C4), DA
Pennebaker's account of the 1967 International Pop Festival where the
performers included Janis Joplin, Otis Redding, Jimi Hendrix, and, in an
extraordinary finale, Ravi Shankar.
</TEXT>
