<HEADLINE>
FT  24 JAN 92 / UK News (Employment): Training providers seek better
relations
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LISA WOOD, Labour Staff
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MEASURES to improve relations between national providers of Youth Training
and training and enterprise councils (Tecs) are to be announced next week
after the withdrawal from the scheme by several large employers and an
industry federation.
The measures, drawn up by the Department of Employment, have persuaded the
British Printing Industries Federation to reverse a previous decision to
stop being a managing agent for Youth Training.
They include arrangements for more of the monitoring visits of YT schemes to
be done by a central unit and fewer by Tecs. The department said the
initiative did not put the Tecs' right to negotiate individual contracts
with providers in jeopardy.
The federation and several large companies announced that they would
withdraw from YT last year because of the burden of negotiating locally with
the 82 Tecs in England and Wales and 22 Local Enterprise Companies (Lecs),
their equivalent in Scotland. Midland Bank and Mothercare have withdrawn for
similar reasons. Only the federation has said it will reverse its decision.
A conference between Tecs and national providers of training will be held on
Tuesday where the changes will be discussed. Mr Robert Jackson, employment
minister, who has been in discussions the providers about the issue will
attend the conference.
A number of changes will be announced. They include:
Standardising the monitoring of quality standards. Although quality criteria
are standard, Tecs have done their own monitoring. Providing a contracting
forum at a convened conference to be held in this month.
</TEXT>
