NATIONALISATION is not the answer to the proposed closure of the Ravenscraig
steel works, Mr Donald Dewar, shadow Scottish secretary, said yesterday, as
he introduced a motion condemning British Steel's repeated failure to
'support and invest in' its Scottish plants, David Owen writes.
Instead, the option of finding a buyer for the plant should be kept open as
long as possible although the chances were slim, he said.
His remarks followed a Scottish National Party assertion that 'public
ownership of steel' in the Scottish economy was needed. 'It is unacceptable
that Scotland should face a future without a steel industry,' said Mr Jim
Sillars, SNP deputy leader.
The government formally applied to the European Commission yesterday to
create an enterprise zone in Lanarkshire in order to offset the impact of
closing the Ravenscraig works.
Last night's debate also followed a government move to shift attention to
more favourable news for the region by announcing that a contract for three
Type 23 frigates had been won by Yarrow Shipbuilders on the Clyde.
The announcement was welcomed by MPs on all sides of the House. Mr George
Galloway (Lab Glasgow Hillhead) advocated naming the vessels Stewart, Lang
and Forsyth in honour of three ministers who, he said, were unlikely to be
much longer in office.
SUNDAY TRADING: Directors of supermarket chains and not local managers
should be the target of any future prosecutions for breaches of the Sunday
trading laws, Mr David Harris (C St Ives) suggested in the Commons
yesterday.
Mrs Angela Rumbold, home office minister, acknowledged cross-party support
for a private member's bill to prevent deregulation of Sunday trading in
England and Wales.
She maintained that it would be 'foolish' to proceed with fresh legislation
before a pending European Court of Justice ruling.
