<HEADLINE>
FT  24 JAN 92 / Call for new R&amp;D audit rules
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW JACK
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE DEFINITION of research-and-development expenditure in company accounts
should be revised to make it more relevant to contemporary business, the
Chartered Institute of Management Accountants has recommended.
Companies are already required to disclose research-and-development (R&amp;D)
expenditure under SSAP 13, an existing accounting standard, and may soon be
required to provide details of other spending that influences future growth.
The institute says in a submission to the Accounting Standards Board (ASB)
that R&amp;D is defined too much in scientific terms, rather than in a way
applicable to most businesses, and so the figure is not taken seriously by
managers.
It neglects types of investment common in service companies, including
expenditure on developing computer software, innovation and training.
The ASB is expected to release a reporting standard in the autumn that will
include recommendations on R&amp;D and other 'revenue expenditure'.
</TEXT>
