<HEADLINE>
FT  24 JAN 92 / Enterprise zones win tax-break extension
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By IAN HAMILTON FAZEY, Northern Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
AN INLAND Revenue ruling has enabled 100 per cent capital allowances in
Britain's enterprise zones to be extended, in special circumstances, by 10
years beyond the life of the zone.
The allowances are disliked by the government and the European Commission
because they distort markets and encourage tax avoidance, but the difficulty
was supposed to be limited to the zones' 10-year lifespan.
The first use of the extended tax break will be in Trafford Park, Greater
Manchester, where it is hoped to salvage part of a flagship project of the
park's development corporation. The project was halted by the effect of the
sharp decline of London commercial property values on its developer,
Rosehaugh.
The corporation, which is a government agency, yesterday relaunched its
Wharfside project along the mainly derelict south bank of Manchester Ship
Canal, opposite the successful Salford Quays.
Now a less ambitious scheme is going ahead with Amec, the Cheshire-based
civil engineering, contracting and property development group.
The Revenue ruling states that if a building contract is awarded on
enterprise-zone land before the zone's life expires, the 100 per cent
capital allowances can be applied to any building started within 10 years of
the contract date.
In the Trafford Park case, the development corporation contracted to sell
the land involved to Amec Properties, which in turn signed a building
contract with Fairclough, another member of the Amec group. The contracts
were signed last August, just before expiry of the enterprise zone.
The Revenue confirmed on December 17 that anything Amec now builds on the
land will enjoy 100 per cent capital allowances. That means that a company
with a tax obligation can buy a building there and pay 35 per cent of the
costs out of its taxes.
The Manchester Ship Canal company, which owns land in the former zone, is
also understood to have agreed a building contract on it before the zone
expired to protect future capital allowances. Other developers in expiring
and extant enterprise zones around the country are believed to have followed
suit.
</TEXT>
