<HEADLINE>
FT  24 JAN 92 / PowerGen to build coal import facility
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JULIET SYCHRAVA
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
POWERGEN, the electricity generator, yesterday proved it was serious about
replacing the coal it buys from British Coal with cheaper imports by
announcing an outlay of Pounds 40m on a new 5m-tonne coal terminal in
Liverpool.
The announcement will add to the uncertainty over the future size of British
Coal now the electricity industry is privatised. British Coal supplies
PowerGen with 26.4m tonnes, falling to 24.6m tonnes in the year to March
1993, and National Power with 44m tonnes, falling to 40m tonnes.
The terminal, which will be designed and built by NEI Clarke Chapman on the
Gladstone Dock, leased by the Mersey Dock and Harbour Company to PowerGen,
is expected to be operating by late next year.
'This will allow PowerGen to withdraw their Fiddlers' Ferry power station
(in Warrington, Cheshire) completely from the UK market,' said Mr Gerard
McCloskey, of the newsletter International Coal Report. He said that
PowerGen was also beginning to squeeze British Coal further by selling
imported coal to industrial customers in competition with British Coal.
National Power, the other large generator, was doing likewise.
British Coal has argued in the past that the two generators were bluffing
about their ability to import coal without pushing the price up - but in
Commons Energy Committee meetings earlier this week National Power
reaffirmed that it planned to be in a position to import half its coal by
the mid 90s. PowerGen said it did not believe that would push prices up, as
there was plenty of spare coal produced worldwide.
PowerGen can already import 5m tonnes to its Kingsnorth power station on the
Thames, and has a joint venture with National Power and Associated British
Ports to build a 10m-tonne terminal at Immingham on the Humber. National
Power is developing two 3m-tonne terminals at Hull and on the Tees, and a
5m-tonne terminal at Bristol.
The two generators' plans to replace British coal with orimulsion, a
bitumen-based fuel, still face strong environmental opposition.
</TEXT>
