<HEADLINE>
FT  24 JAN 92 / Algerian economic rescue plan drawn up
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT GRAHAM and FRANCIS GHILES
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   ALGIERS
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
THE Algerian government has drawn up an emergency plan to revive the
economy, channelling funds into industry, public works projects and housing.
The authorities have had to draw down on precious resources and stimulate
growth faster than originally intended in order to satisfy the disaffected
electorate, half of whom voted for the Islamic Salvation Front (FIS) in the
recently annulled elections.
Economic recovery is regarded by senior officials as a central element in
retaining social stability and drawing support away from the FIS. The FIS is
credited with having drawn much of its support from cities, where youth
unemployment is more than 25 per cent and the housing shortage is acute.
To increase stagnant output and boost social spending, the government will
raise imports from Dollars 7.6bn (Pounds 4.2bn) to Dollars 9bn. Of this,
Dollars 200m will be added to last year's food import bill of Dollars 1.7bn.
Imports of intermediate goods for industry will increase from Dollars 2.6bn
to Dollars 3.2bn.
The authorities want to streamline bureaucratic procedures blocking the use
of multilateral credits, some dating from the early 1980s.
The plan, expected to be announced by the weekend, is operating with tight
constraints imposed by the country's heavy burden of debt service and scarce
foreign reserves. The authorities are counting on a reduction in the annual
cost of servicing medium- and long-term debt from Dollars 9.3bn last year to
Dollars 7.6bn.
Essential to this calculation is the completion of the Dollars 1.5bn
refinancing package with the commercial banks, under negotiation for 18
months. The completion of this refinancing was being held up by Bankers
Trust before elections in the second round of Algeria's first multi-party
elections were annulled.
The US bank is understood to have bought some Dollars 56m worth of Algerian
paper on the secondary market and is unhappy to see the redemption date of
this paper pushed back - inevitable if the refinancing package goes through.
However, Algerian authorities are concerned that political uncertainties
could now influence other banks and so delay the arrival of funds. The
outcome of these negotiations could affect further disbursements of the EC's
Ecu400m (Pounds 285.2m) loan and in turn condition the government's attitude
towards Dollars 23.5bn foreign debt as a whole.
Until now successive governments have been adamant in their refusal to
contemplate rescheduling or default.
Even with this assistance, the debt burden will account for more than 60 per
cent of the Dollars 11.3bn income anticipated from 1992 sales of oil, gas,
condensates and refined products.
For the basket of these four items, the Finance Ministry has calculated an
average price equivalent to Dollars 21 a barrel, and income from
hydrocarbons sales will be down Dollars 1bn overall on 1991.
Net hard currency reserves stand at Dollars 1bn, plus Dollars 2bn in gold
which previous governments have refused to touch.
Another key to the emergency plan will be the attitude of international oil
companies to the two-month-old amendments to the 1986 hydrocarbons law which
allowed foreign companies to enter joint ventures in already developed
oilfields. Some 20 companies have expressed an interest and their
participation would immediately inject much-needed hard cash.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 4
</PAGE>
