FT  24 JAN 92 / Bonn takes tough line on Soviet debt
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By QUENTIN PEEL
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   BONN
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
FORMER Soviet republics like Ukraine, which have yet to sign the
western-inspired memorandum of understanding on repaying the debts of the
former Soviet Union, could be refused membership of the International
Monetary Fund.
Germany will press at the G7 meeting to block membership for those not
prepared to honour Soviet debts, not with the aim of excluding them, but
rather to force them into line.
Ukraine is by far the most important of the four which have so far refused
to accept responsibility. The others are Azerbaijan, Georgia and Uzbekistan.
Estonia, Latvia and Lithuania, which were forcibly incorporated into the
Soviet Union in 1940, have rejected responsibility for a share of the Soviet
debt apart from that related to projects in the Baltic states.
Germany, the largest creditor of the former Soviet Union, is determined that
'a country cannot become a member of the IMF without accepting its
responsibility for its debts,' according to officials in Bonn. That means in
effect that they will be compelled to sign the memorandum of understanding.
At the same time Germany is hoping for the speediest possible incorporation
of the ex-Soviet republics into the IMF, in order to give them access both
to credits and expertise.
Officials in Bonn believe that a letter of intent on a Fund programme for
Russia could be agreed by the end of February, submitted to the IMF board in
March, and full membership of the Fund could follow in April, clearing the
way for IMF credits.
The most difficult problem is that of quotas for the former Soviet republics
within the fund: the debate ranges from a lower limit of 3 per cent, to an
upper limit of 6 per cent. The difference concerns whether intra-republican
trade is taken into account: if the former Soviet Union had joined as a
single unit, such trade would not have been considered. However given
current fragmentation, intra-republican links have become external trade.
Eight ex-Soviet republics have applied to join the fund.
</TEXT>
