<HEADLINE>
FT  24 JAN 92 / Investment in Malaysia falls
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LIM SIONG HOON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   KUALA LUMPUR
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
PROPOSALS to restrict the level of foreign participation and shareholdings
have led to a large drop in the number of applications for manufacturing
ventures in Malaysia. The value of inward investments last year fell by 52
per cent to MDollars 23.6bn (Dollars 8.7bn) from MDollars 48.8bn in 1990.
Ms Rafidah Aziz, international trade and industry minister, attributed the
drop to the unusually large number of investment applications in previous
years and to the general climate of uncertainty facing foreign investors.
Proposed investments with majority foreign shareholding dropped from
MDollars 13.2bn in 1990 to MDollars 2bn last year, while those wholly
foreign-owned fell from MDollars 13.7bn to MDollars 10.9bn.
Last year, the Malaysian budget included tough qualifying rules and
shareholding requirements for foreign investors and abolished tax holidays.
Malaysia says the new rules are necessary to stem the deterioration in the
national current account deficits, projected to reach 10 per cent or more of
GNP.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
