<HEADLINE>
FT  23 JAN 92 / World Stock Markets (America): Late programme trading gives
Dow sharp boost
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By KAREN ZAGOR
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Wall Street
US STOCK prices wavered in a narrowly mixed range for most of yesterday, as
the market digested a surfeit of corporate results, but a late round of
programme trading pushed the market sharply higher, writes Karen Zagor in
New York.
The Dow Jones Industrial Average, which retreated 30.64 on Tuesday, closed
32.42 ahead at 3,255.81 after a fairly heavy New York SE volume of 228m
shares. Advances outpaced declines by 1,132 to 618. The Standard &amp; Poor's
500 rose 5.49 to 418.13.
Shares started to move up in the afternoon following a successful two-year
note auction, but it was the computer-driven programmes that triggered the
late rally.
Baxter International lost Dollars  3/8 to Dollars 37 in heavy trading on
news that the company's supply contract with Hospital Corp, valued at
Dollars 250m a year, might be in jeopardy. Hospital Corp is allowing its
units to accept bids for some supplies.
Monsanto tumbled Dollars 2 1/8 to Dollars 67 after the big US chemical
company unveiled 1991 earnings of Dollars 296m, down 45 per cent from the
previous year's figure.
Banc One, the strong mid-western commercial banking group, added Dollars 1
1/2 at Dollars 49 5/8 on the back of a 25 per cent rise in 1991 net profits
to Dollars 529.5m.
Minnesota Mining and Manufacturing receded Dollars 1 to Dollars 96 1/8 on
reporting disappointing fourth-quarter earnings of Dollars 1.18 a share,
against Dollars 1.34 a year earlier. The company also warned that it expects
a difficult start to 1992.
Browning Ferris edged Dollars  1/8 lower to Dollars 22 5/8 after posting
first-quarter earnings of 26 cents a share, compared with 40 cents a year
ago.
Campbell Soup advanced Dollars 2 1/4 to Dollars 39 after Goldman Sachs added
the stock to its recommended list.
News that Conseco had agreed to buy Bankers Life &amp; Casualty for Dollars 600m
from ICH Corp lifted Conseco's stock Dollars 5 to Dollars 69 3/4 . The issue
has traded in a range of Dollars 13 3/4 to Dollars 70 in the last year. On
the American Stock Exchange, ICH put on Dollars  1/4 to Dollars 4 3/8 .
A strong buy rating by Merrill Lynch on Delta Air Lines' stock boosted the
issue Dollars 2 3/8 to Dollars 74 1/4 . Among other airlines, AMR rose
Dollars 1 1/4 to Dollars 74 1/8 and UAL gained Dollars 1 3/8 to Dollars 150
7/8 . USAir firmed Dollars  7/8 to Dollars 16 3/8 . Its results were
released after the market closed.
Computer Associates jumped Dollars 3 1/4 to Dollars 15 1/8 after the company
turned in third-quarter earnings of 43 cents a share against 35 cents a year
earlier.
The secondary market posted stronger gains than the primary market, with the
Nasdaq composite ending 15.81 up at 620.68.
Henley Group advanced Dollars 3 to Dollars 28 3/4 . The manufacturer said it
was creating a board committee to consider a recapitalisation plan that
would distribute Dollars 250m to shareholders.
Canada
TORONTO stocks rebounded from morning weakness to end firmer on balance. The
composite index was finally 18.3 ahead at 3,638.8, after a day's low of
3,607.6. Rises led declines by 327 to 253 following volume of 27.9m shares,
against 31.7m.
Dofasco gained CDollars  1/2 to CDollars 18 1/2 . The company's Algoma Steel
unit announced a major restructuring which, among other things, would give
Algoma's employees 60 per cent ownership of the unit and would turn the
other 40 per cent over to Algoma's creditors and preferred shareholders.
Deprenyl Research was up CDollars  1/2 at CDollars 22 3/8 . The company said
its board recommended a two-for-one stock split.
</TEXT>
