<HEADLINE>
FT  23 JAN 92 / International Capital Markets: CBOT to support top
derivative investors
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By BARBARA DURR
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   CHICAGO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
THE Chicago Board of Trade, the world's largest futures exchange, intends to
take measures to better accommodate the increasing number of large
institutional investors which use futures and options.
The CBOT board has proposed to lift position limits on three of the
exchange's main financial contracts, the Treasury bond and the five and
10-year Treasury note futures. The move must be approved by the Commodity
Futures Trading Commission. Option limits on those contracts would remain
the same.
The board also approved regulations that will allow member firms to provide
average prices and order quantities when executing large orders or series of
orders. The aim is to make the market more efficient for fund managers.
The Chicago Mercantile Exchange earlier this month won approval from the
CFTC to lift position limits on futures and options on Eurodollars and
leading currencies. It cited the need to accommodate the trading
requirements of large managed funds.
Late last year, the CME put in place a system for average pricing of large
orders.
Managed funds are estimated to contain as much as Dollars 30bn, up from just
Dollars 10bn at the start of 1990.
</TEXT>
