<HEADLINE>
FT  23 JAN 92 / International Company News: Bombardier buys controlling
stake in de Havilland
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By BERNARD SIMON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   TORONTO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
BOMBARDIER, the Montreal-based transport equipment maker, is expanding its
airframe manufacturing business by buying a 51 per cent interest in
loss-making de Havilland of Canada with assistance from the Canadian and
Ontario governments.
A new corporate entity, to be known as de Havilland Inc, is to purchase
assets worth CDollars 260m (USDollars 224.10m) from Boeing of Seattle, which
has owned de Havilland since 1986. Boeing will receive CDollars 70m in cash.
The buyers will also assume liabilities of about CDollars 190m.
The province of Ontario will have a 49 per cent equity stake in de
Havilland, but Bombardier will have the right to acquire that interest after
four years. Ontario and the federal government have also provided various
other financial inducements.
The two governments have been desperate to find a buyer for de Havilland
since a bid by Aerospatiale of France and Italy's Alenia was blocked by the
European Commission last September. The EC contended that the proposed
takeover would have created a dominant player in the European commuter
aircraft industry.
The 63-year-old company has enormous symbolic value to Canada. Maker of such
famous aircraft as the Tiger Moth, the Mosquito and the Twin Otter, it is
one of only two airframe builders in Canada and one of the biggest
industrial employers in the Toronto area.
De Havilland's only remaining product is the twin-engined Dash-8.
The de Havilland purchase marks Bombardier's fourth investment in an
aircraft manufacturer. It already controls Short Bros of Belfast, the US
business jet maker Learjet, and Canadair, the Montreal-based manufacturer of
business jets and fire-fighting aircraft.
Boeing put de Havilland on the block almost two years ago after losing
patience with the company, which last made a profit in 1982. Although its
products are widely respected, de Havilland has been bedevilled by high
costs, low productivity and uncertainty over its future.
</TEXT>
