<HEADLINE>
FT  23 JAN 92 / International Company News: Union Pacific lifts income by 8%
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NIKKI TAIT
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
UNION PACIFIC, one of the largest US railroad companies, kicked off the
sector's reporting season with news of an 8 per cent improvement in
fourth-quarter operating income at Dollars 359m.
At the after-tax level, this reduced to a 5 per cent gain, but the railroad
operations earned Dollars 163m, up 13 per cent on the previous year.
The company said the operating environment throughout 1991 was 'very
difficult', but car loadings during the 12 months had increased by around 4
per cent, despite an industry drop of 3 per cent.
It also held out some hope for an improvement in 1992. 'We remain cautiously
optimistic about the coming year,' commented Mr Drew Lewis, Union Pacific's
chief executive.
Nevertheless, shares in Union Pacific, whose track is concentrated west of
the Mississippi, still closed Dollars 1 lower at Dollars 46 3/4 .
Later in the day, CSX, another of the large transportation companies, also
reported an underlying 4 per cent increase in fourth-quarter net earnings,
to Dollars 134m. The company had already warned of a Dollars 755m one-off
charge to cover labour reductions and other productivity moves, and after
this, the net loss for the quarter was Dollars 356m. The net loss for the
year, after the charge, was Dollars 272m - compared with 1990's profit of
Dollars 416m.
Like CSX, Union Pacific figures for the full year bear the brunt of a hefty
Dollars 870m pre-tax special charge, taken in the third quarter to cover
labour productivity changes, including large redundancies, and the
abandonment of certain light-used track. After this charge, 1991 operating
profits fell from Dollars 1.32bn to Dollars 461m, on revenues of Dollars
7.02bn, against Dollars 6.96bn. Net income fell to Dollars 64m, against
Dollars 618m in the previous year.
Meanwhile, at Santa Fe Pacific - a third railroad operator owning the
Atchison, Topeka and Santa Fe Railway, together with other minerals and
pipeline interests - fourth-quarter results showed a Dollars 32.8m profit
after tax, a considerable advance on the Dollars 54.6m loss in the same
period a year earlier. Operating profits from the rail business reached
Dollars 65.1m, compared with Dollars 22.4m in the final quarter of 1990,
with car loadings up by 8 per cent.
For the full year, net income was Dollars 96.4m against a Dollars 111.8m
loss. The shares closed Dollars  3/8 down at Dollars 12 3/4 .
</TEXT>
