<HEADLINE>
FT  23 JAN 92 / UK Company News: Independent's owner hopes for modest profit
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RAYMOND SNODDY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
NEWSPAPER Publishing, owner of The Independent and the Independent on
Sunday, is hoping for a modest profit in the year to September in spite of
one of the worst advertising recessions for broadsheet newspapers for
decades.
Last year NP incurred pre-tax losses of Pounds 10.3m, although this included
a Pounds 1.5m provision for redundancy costs. Last September the company
completed an Pounds 8.25m refinancing.
Now there are growing hopes that a taxable profit of about Pounds 500,000 is
possible this year even though there are still few signs of the recession
lifting.
The first hint of financially better times for The Independent came
yesterday at NP's annual meeting when Mr Andreas Whittam Smith, editor and
chief executive, said the company had achieved a 'worthwhile' profit in its
first quarter. This compares with a loss of Pounds 1m for the same period in
1990.
The company's first quarter includes the strong newspaper advertising months
of October and November and the second quarter will be much more difficult.
'Moreover, the recession still lies heavily on our readers and on our
advertising customers. There is no buoyancy in our markets,' Mr Whittam
Smith said.
'Nonetheless we have got ourselves into a position in which we can make
progress in difficult trading conditions,' he added.
It is clear that the company hopes that the 'progress' will include a year
in the black, even if only modestly so.
</TEXT>
