<HEADLINE>
FT  23 JAN 92 / Stanhope, Rosehaugh merger talks cease
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By VANESSA HOULDER, Property Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
ROSEHAUGH and Stanhope, the indebted property companies which jointly own
the Broadgate office complex in the City of London, yesterday called a halt
to their merger talks.
The companies issued a statement to the stock exchange, saying 'agreement is
unlikely in the near future and . . . a further period of prolonged
uncertainty would not be in the best interests of shareholders'. The news
sent Stanhope's share price down from 25p to 23.5p and Rosehaugh's share
price down from 6 1/2 p to 5 1/4 p.
Ever since the talks were announced last summer, progress has been slow. One
of the problems facing the groups was getting agreement among their 70
banks. The banks, which had loans secured against more solid assets, were
concerned that a merger and reconstruction could impair the quality of their
loans.
Rosehaugh, which announced the breach of its covenants and pre-tax losses of
Pounds 227m in December, issued a statement to the stock exchange yesterday
which said discussions with its banks had always been on the basis that it
would remain an independent company.
Rosehaugh is trying to negotiate a medium-term facility with its banks. It
has a stand-still agreement until the end of the month which may need to be
renewed.
Both companies believed merger discussions might resume.
Stanhope, which was the stronger party in the talks, announced annual
pre-tax losses of Pounds 77m and a 30 per cent fall in net asset value in
October.
Lex, Page 20
</TEXT>
