<HEADLINE>
FT  23 JAN 92 / Observer: Guru glut
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
It seems only yesterday that young Treasury economists were regularly
deserting to the City, doubling their salaries as they went. But now I hear
that Donald Franklin, Schroders' chief economist, has voluntarily moved the
other way to become a mere Treasury indian, or economic adviser, salary
range Pounds 24-37K.
Why? Boredom, he says; after nine years of churning out forecasts (a
Nintendo-like activity these days) he hungers for the red meat of policy.
Well, maybe; but real-life markets take little notice of economic forecasts
these days. As David Morrison of Goldman Sachs sourly remarked this week:
'It seems like an inefficient use of time to try to assess 'economic
pressures'.' Perhaps soon redundant, too.
