<HEADLINE>
FT  23 JAN 92 / Parliament and Politics: Lamont cornered by Commons
pragmatism - Ivo Dawnay on legislative considerations facing the chancellor
as he prepares his pre-election Budget
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By IVO DAWNAY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
COULD Mr Norman Lamont use his Budget to present the electorate with an
appetising smorgasbord of fiscal goodies, then, just two days later, have
the prime minister call a general election and defy the Labour party to vote
them down?
Britain's electoral and legislative machinery may be brutal, but it is not
quite as barbaric as that.
Mr Lamont, as chancellor, can certainly use his Budget speech to present a
picture of what the Tories have in mind for the future. He can - and
undoubtedly will - also devote some part of it to outlining glorious
economic prospects ahead.
He can thus convey the message that voters must choose between tax-cutting
Tories and spendthrift Labourites.
But what he cannot do is table a legislative package of fiscal measures that
he has no intention of actually passing through the House.
Budgets normally need at least eight weeks to complete their parliamentary
passage and have until the beginning of the summer recess at the end of July
to do so. With an election imminent, however, the chancellor must choose
carefully among controversial items on his menu.
If, as some have suggested, Mr Major calls an election within two or three
days of the chancellor resuming his seat on the green leather front bench,
then Mr Lamont will know beforehand that there may be only at best two or
three days of parliamentary time to get a tiny bill through the House.
Under normal procedures, temporary budget 'resolutions' are enforced as soon
as the chancellor has spoken on the Tuesday. Those allow only normal revenue
activities - the collection of income taxes or Customs and Excise-supervised
changes in, for example, cigarette duties - to come into force for a limited
period.
On the following Monday - after three days of debate - two sample
resolutions are presented, debated and passed; immediately prompting the
full Finance Bill to be tabled. Some two to five weeks later (after the
Easter recess) the bill then comes to its formal second reading before
passing the usual committee stage, navigating the Lords and returning for
final Commons ratification.
If an election is to interrupt that process, the chancellor must table only
what he knows he can get through in a few hours of Commons time. That
process means that the reach of the budget must inevitably be heavily
curtailed.
The chancellor is not entirely hedged in. He can use the 'usual channels' -
Commons-speak for informal negotiations with Labour's business managers - to
compromise on the easier parts of the package like the simple annual
uprating of inflation-indexed taxes or allowances.
For the contentious, headline-grabbing items - above all a possible cut in
the standard rate of income tax - he must choose what is feasible and what
is not.
If by the Monday after Budget Day an election has already been called, there
may be only two or three days of business before a formal dissolution must
take place. While any new government can table another Budget after the
election is over, Britain cannot be without any Finance Bill in the interim.
What is now fascinating connoisseurs of procedure is whether a skilled
reading of the Budget speech and its legislative proposals will prove
sufficiently explicit to predict the election date accurately - even before
the prime minister officially announces it.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
