<HEADLINE>
FT  23 JAN 92 / Parliament and Politics: Chancellor says recovery 'not yet
established' - Autumn Statement Debate
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By IVOR OWEN and DAVID OWEN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MR Norman Lamont, the chancellor, told the Commons last night that recovery
from the recession 'had not yet become firmly established'.
His insistence that foundations for recovery 'are in place' and that
consumer spending was set to increase, was cheered by government supporters
but derided by the opposition in another pre-election slanging match.
Mr John Smith, shadow chancellor, condemned 'bogus forecasts' made by Mr
Lamont in his autumn statement, and again called for enhanced capital
allowances to be included in the Budget on March 10 to 'move out of
recession to investment-led recovery'.
The autumn statement - approved by a government majority of 90 (317-227) -
was said by Mr Smith to have contained 'rubbish' forecasts drawn up as part
of a mythical economic scenario designed for a November general election
which failed to materialise.
He insisted: 'The fact is that the economy is stagnant and, at the very
best, is bumping along the bottom'.
Mr Lamont underlined his disappointment that the signs of recovery which he
highlighted last summer had not been sustained.
'There remain good grounds for believing that recovery will become firmly
established in the course of 1992,' he said.
The chancellor said the rapid fall in inflation and the consequent increase
in real incomes for those in work meant there was 'very considerable pent-up
demand in the economy'.
He emphasised the significance of the response being made by manufacturers
and retailers to weak demand - cuts in prices and costs.
Mr Nick Budgen (C Wolverhampton South West) and Mr Tony Favell (C Stockport)
criticised the decision to include sterling in the exchange rate mechanism
of the European Monetary System.
Mr Budgen contended that if the Conservative party lost the general election
it would be because of policies initiated by Mr Nigel Lawson, the former
chancellor, in 1985 and which culminated in the decision to join the ERM.
Mr Tony Benn, MP for Chesterfield and one of 25 Labour backbenchers who
backed a parliamentary motion (not debated) which attributed the recession
to 'the uncontrolled operation of market forces', feared a slump comparable
to that experienced in the 1930s.
Mrs Margaret Beckett, shadow chief secretary to the Treasury, claimed that
96 per cent of families would be better off as a result of the overall
effect of Labour's commitment to extend the coverage of national insurance
contributions and increase the top rate of income tax.
Mr Alan Beith, Liberal Democrat Treasury spokesman, questioned whether
autumn statements represented a serious attempt to forecast future economic
trends and said that they usually appeared to have been massaged in a bid to
instil the economic confidence ministers understandably sought.
</TEXT>
