<HEADLINE>
FT  23 JAN 92 / Parliament and Politics: Heseltine hints at legislation -
Poll Tax Non-payment
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT RICE and ALISON SMITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THERE were signs last night that the government was ready to take urgent
action to legislate in response to pressure to ease confusion surrounding
the use of computer evidence in poll tax cases.
The uncertainty threatens to deprive local authorities of any realistic
possibility of recovering outstanding poll tax.
The increasing difficulties about computer evidence come as the poll tax is
emerging as a critical election issue. Its political profile is likely to
raise even higher in the coming weeks, as more local authorities set their
budgets for the coming year.
Camden Council in north London called on the government to 'act now to end
the poll tax chaos', after a decision yesterday by the Clerkenwell
stipendiary magistrate that the council was not allowed to rely on computer
records as evidence of non-payment in default actions against 12 Camden
residents.
'We shall review the situation most urgently and come forward with the
answers very shortly. Obviously it requires a legislative decision. The
government has to decide how to act in the circumstances,' Mr Michael
Heseltine, the environment secretary, said last night on Channel Four news.
Ministers are aware, however, that if they legislate to close the loophole
in the law, they will effectively admit that it exists, casting doubt on the
validity of 5m poll tax cases dealt with since April 1990.
Meanwhile, Labour highlighted the continuing sensitivity of the Poll Tax by
stepping up claims that ministers were considering delaying sending out
bills.
Mr Bryan Gould, shadow environment secretary, challenged ministers to say
whether the requirement for those on low incomes to pay a minimum 20 per
cent contribution to the poll tax would be removed in the Budget.
Ministers, who attacked opposition MPs for involvement in non-payment
campaigns, have ruled out fundamental changes to the poll tax, and the
government emphasised yesterday that those required to pay the minimun
contribution were given the money to do so through social security benefits.
Labour, however, remain convinced that the government intends in some way to
soften the impact of the tax in its final year.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 10
</PAGE>
