<HEADLINE>
FT  23 JAN 92 / Parliament and Politics: Bank codes of practice criticised -
News in Brief
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHARLES BATCHELOR
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE BANKING codes for personal and business customers announced by the banks
in recent weeks were criticised as being inadequate by consumer and business
groups at a Commons Treasury committee hearing yesterday, Charles Batchelor
writes.
The Consumers' Association described the personal code as 'lacking the
features you would normally expect to see from progressive organisations in
today's marketplace'. The Confederation of British Industry said the
business codes were 'not the final word'.
The British Bankers' Association last month announced details of a common
code of practice for dealing with personal customers for the UK banks and
building societies which will come into effect on March 16. Individual
business banking codes have been introduced by the main UK banks in recent
weeks in response to government pressure.
*****
EDUCATION: Student indebtedness is increasing, with the lack of vacation
jobs and the government's withdrawal of welfare benefits the main causes,
the committee of vice-chancellors (CVCP) told the Commons education
committee yesterday.
The CVCP said there was no evidence of any increase in drop-out rates as a
result. There has been a slight decrease - although not for long enough to
signify a trend.
Sir Gordon Higginson, vice-chancellor of Southampton University, told the
committee: 'Some of our students are having a desperate time. We need a
better system (of student financial support) and a safety net.'
*****
HOUSING: Mortgage lenders are expected to announce within the next few weeks
measures to counter home repossessions, Mr Michael Heseltine, the
environment secretary, said. He told MPs he had spoken yesterday morning to
Mr Mark Boleat, the director-general of the Council of Mortgage Lenders, and
expected the lending institutions to make announcements within the next two
to three weeks.
Recent discussions with building societies, banks and housing associations
led to a commitment to measures aimed at aiding homeowners.
</TEXT>
