<HEADLINE>
FT  23 JAN 92 / Elections introduced for accountancy post
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW JACK
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE ELECTION for vice-president of the Institute of Chartered Accountants in
England and Wales is be contested for the first time, with three candidates
standing for the post.
Mr Patrick Brenan, a director of Minories Finance; Mr Chris Swinson,
national managing partner of BDO Binder Hamlyn, the seventh-largest
accountancy firm by fee income last year; and Mr Roger Lawson, a director of
3i, the venture capital group, have all been nominated.
The position of vice-president has traditionally been nominated by the
president's advisory committee, which at present has just eight senior
members, and rubber-stamped at a meeting of the council in June.
Only a handful have ever been non-practising members.
The contest is only a partial movement towards democracy. The vice-president
takes office in June and normally automatically becomes deputy president the
following year and president the year after. In addition, only the 78
elected members of the council of the institute can vote, a process that
will take place early next month.
Mr Brenan has already issued a short manifesto saying the council has failed
to act in the public interest against 'indefensible practices' and has not
put forward policies in a sufficiently vigorous way.
Mr Lawson is still preparing a statement but said yesterday that his main
hope was to ensure that the institute resisted pressures that might cause it
to split in two, between auditors and other accountants.
Commenting on the introduction of elections, he said: 'It's a major move
forward. I think we're finally moving into the twentieth century.'
</TEXT>
