<HEADLINE>
FT  23 JAN 92 / Channel tunnel builders win right to halt work
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW TAYLOR, Construction Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
BRITISH and French contractors building the Channel tunnel were yesterday
given permission by the British Court of Appeal to renew their threat to
stop work on part of the Pounds 8bn project unless they are paid more money.
Lord Justices Neill, Woolf and Staughton said they would not grant an
injunction preventing the contractors from halting work on installing a
cooling system in the twin rail tunnels.
They also released the construction companies from a High Court undertaking
not to halt work without giving 14 days' warning to Eurotunnel, the Channel
tunnel operator.
Eurotunnel said last night it was considering seeking leave to appeal to the
Lords.
Transmanche, a consortium of five British and five French construction
groups, issued its threat to stop work last October after a disagreement
with Eurotunnel over who should pay for a huge increase in the cost of the
project. Costs had risen since 1987 from Pounds 4.8bn to Pounds 8.05bn.
The two sides are at present involved in negotiations to resolve the
dispute. A stoppage is unlikely while talks continue.
Members of the consortium have indicated that discussions have been going
well, although a gap still exists between the two sides.
Lord Staughton said an English court should not grant an interim injunction
in a disagreement that all the parties had agreed ought to go to arbitration
abroad.
The Channel tunnel contract, which is subject to both British and French
law, provides for disputes to be referred first to a panel of three
independent experts and then to arbitration in Brussels.
Any application for an injunction, therefore, should be made to Brussels,
Lord Staughton said.
Transmanche had told the court it was entitled to suspend work because of
alleged breaches of contract by Eurotunnel in funding the installation of
the cooling system. Lord Staughton said that if the contract had been
subject simply to English law, that argument would have faced some
difficulty.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
