<HEADLINE>
FT  23 JAN 92 / UK News (Employment): Cohse plans database for local NHS
bargaining
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID GOODHART, Labour Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
COHSE, the health service union, said yesterday it was going to give its
branches access to a comprehensive pay database to help them deal with local
bargaining in the National Health Service.
NHS bargaining has traditionally been highly centralised but, with the
growth of self-governing trusts, unions are resigned to a fragmentation of
bargaining.
Few trusts have so far broken away from NHS pay rates and industrial
relations structures. The best-known exceptions are Northumbria Ambulance
Service and Guy's Hospital, in London.
One health union official said yesterday: 'If the Tories win the election
most of the trust personnel directors will dust off their plans for radical
changes.'
Trusts, especially in south-east England, are expected in many cases to want
to pay above existing NHS rates and increase differentials in order to
attract staff.
In some areas, however, they are expected to seek to cut pay. A trust in
Dorset recently tried to employ a radiographer on less favourable terms and
conditions than current NHS rates, but the unions ensured that nobody
applied for the job.
Nupe, the public-service union, said it had won six race-discrimination
cases in the past month.
</TEXT>
