<BYLINE>
   By BETHAN HUTTON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A run for their money: Dairy Crest and McVities, two of the main supporters
of British athletics, have withdrawn from sponsorship within weeks of each
other, Bethan Hutton writes.
Dairy Crest said it was delighted with the increase in public awareness it
had achieved through athletics sponsorship - with its name appearing on such
famous chests as that of sprinter Linford Christie, above. The decision was
made because of the recession and a change in marketing objectives.
McVities cited the same reasons for its withdrawal. A third big sponsor,
ParcelForce, withdrew last year.
Tony Ward, an official of the British Athletic Federation, said: 'The
recession has finally caught up with us.' However, he added that a new
three-year sponsorship package with TSB, the banking group, had recently
been agreed while others were due to be announced soon.
Mr Ian Muir, Institute of Sports Sponsorship chairman, said companies were
becoming more professional about sponsorship and seeking to meet specific
marketing objectives.
