FT  23 JAN 92 / UK News (Employment): EETPU's return to TUC eased
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHAEL SMITH, Labour Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MR NORMAN WILLIS, general secretary of the Trades Union Congress, gave a
strong indication yesterday that he did not expect the EETPU electricians'
union to face stiff financial penalties if it reaffiliated to the TUC.
The EETPU was expelled from the TUC three years ago amid warnings that if it
rejoined it would have to pay affiliation fees for all the time it was
outside the organisation. The total already amounts to more than Pounds 1m.
Mr Willis told the TUC general council yesterday that a merger between the
EETPU and the AEU engineering union, which is likely in March and has
prompted the reaffiliation discussion, was to be welcomed.
The possible return of the EETPU has prompted letters of concern from eight
unions: the probation officers' union Napo, the National Union of
Journalists, the Prison Officers Association, the Civil Service union NUCPS,
the construction union Ucatt, the general technical union MSF, the Fire
Brigades Union and the breakaway electricians' union EPIU.
The primary concern is not money, although some unions are likely to press
for the full back-affiliation fees to be paid, but rather the existence
within the EETPU of several organisations that have broken away from
TUC-affiliated unions.
Union leaders are also seeking guarantees that the EETPU in the merged union
would abandon what they see as membership poaching.
The EETPU was expelled after failing to obey a TUC ruling to withdraw from
two single-union deals.
</TEXT>
