<HEADLINE>
FT  23 JAN 92 / UK News (Employment): Tecs to confront Howard over planned
training cuts
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LISA WOOD, Labour Staff
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
CHIEF executives from more than half of the 82 Training and Enterprise
Councils (Tecs) took the unprecedented step yesterday of asking their
chairmen to take concerns over proposed cuts in training funds directly to
the government.
G10, the group of 10 chairmen that presents the views of Tecs to Mr Michael
Howard, employment secretary, meets on Monday to discuss the present round
of negotiations over this year's Tec budgets.
It is understood that most of the 82 chief executives in England and Wales
broadly support the concerns of the 42 who met yesterday in Derby.
The Department of Employment plans a 'substantial reduction' in the weekly
contributions for Youth Training, its main scheme for people aged 16 to 18,
and for Employment Training, the scheme for long-unemployed adults.
The department, under pressure from the Treasury, wants increased volumes of
training in 1992-93 for roughly the same amount of money as in 1991-92.
The chief executives said yesterday that although it was up to Tecs to
negotiate individually with the government there was also room for a common
approach. They feared that if cuts were made they would not be able to
guarantee training places to all young people who wanted them. They also
worry that quality of training may deteriorate.
One chief executive said: 'We are concerned that we might not be able to
deliver high-quality qualifications.'
The chief executives said they thought the Treasury saw Tecs as deliverers
of the two main training programmes and had little understanding of their
wider role, such as prompting employers to improve their own training.
Apex Trust, the charity that provides training and job help for
ex-offenders, was placed in administration by the High Court today.
The court-appointed administrators have about four weeks to try to bring off
a rescue operation for the financially troubled trust.
</TEXT>
