<HEADLINE>
FT  23 JAN 92 / Scottish optimism declines
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JAMES BUXTON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
BUSINESSES in Scotland see no sign of an economic upturn and are less
optimistic than they were three months ago, according to the latest Scottish
Chambers of Commerce quarterly survey, James Buxton writes.
The recession has affected Scotland less severely than some other parts of
Britain, but demand remains stagnant or contracting in all main sectors,
while manufacturers' stocks continue to run down.
All told, 1,229 companies responded to the survey. In manufacturing, only 2
per cent of respondents were more optimistic than they were three months
ago, when the balance was 12 per cent. In retailing, only 2 per cent
reported greater optimism, compared with 18 per cent in the previous
quarter, and in wholesaling a net balance of 4 per cent was less confident.
In the tourist industry, a balance of 24 per cent showed more optimism than
three months previously. Confidence in the construction industry
deteriorated.
Investment is falling and where it exists is mainly devoted to replacing or
improving existing plant rather than gearing up for expansion.
</TEXT>
