<HEADLINE>
FT  23 JAN 92 / Sir Charles Villiers, chairman of BSC: Obituary
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
SIR Charles Villiers, who was chairman of the British Steel Corporation
between 1976 and 1980, one of its most traumatic periods, died yesterday
aged 79.
Sir Charles, a well-intentioned, kind and thoughtful man, was one of the
most beleaguered BSC chairmen. The closure programme he enacted - the
workforce was reduced from 208,000 to 166,000 - provoked a bitter strike
during which he lost the support of his political masters.
In spite of the criticisms of his performance, his time as chairman was
pivotal in the corporation's development, marking the end of the
over-ambitious expansion plans drawn up in the early 1970s and the start of
the cost-cutting that turned British Steel into one of the most profitable
steelmakers in Europe by the end of the 1980s.
Sir Charles was groomed for a career in the City by his education at Eton
and New College, Oxford. He served in the Grenadier Guards during the Second
World War, winning the Military Cross in 1945 after parachuting into
Yugoslavia to fight alongside Tito's partisans.
After the war he moved briskly into a string of banking jobs, eventually
becoming managing director of J. Henry Schroder Wagg, the merchant bank.
In 1968 he was appointed chairman of the Industrial Reorganisation
Corporation, where he recruited a team of ambitious young people who went on
to senior posts in British industry - including Sir Christopher Hogg,
chairman of Courtaulds, and Sir Alastair Morton, the deputy chairman of
Eurotunnel.
After leaving British Steel, his main achievement was a book on British
industry entitled Start Again Britain, in which he wrote of the downward
spiral in which the country was caught. It would not escape 'unless we make
a drastic effort to break out of it on a scale so far not contemplated'.
Sir Charles leaves a wife, two daughters and a son.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
