<HEADLINE>
FT  23 JAN 92 / Businesses expect delay in recovery
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PETER MARSH, Economics Staff
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE ECONOMIC recovery is likely to be postponed from the second to the third
quarter of this year, the Association of British Chambers of Commerce said
yesterday.
That assessment emerged from the association's latest quarterly survey of
business opinion, which reported a decline in confidence compared with the
third quarter of last year. It also found a poorer outlook for investment
and employment.
The survey was based on questions last month to nearly 7,500 manufacturing
and service companies. One finding was that unemployment will continue to
rise, a factor likely to damp consumer confidence and hold back demand for
credit.
The association warned that with base rates stuck at 10.5 per cent and a
weak pound preventing the government from cutting the cost of borrowing,
real interest rates were rising as inflation fell. High real rates 'may act
as a depressant to economic performance'.
Another factor delaying recovery was uncertainty about the election.
Better news for Mr Norman Lamont, the chancellor, came with signs of a rise
in exports. The association warned, however, that a slowdown in big overseas
markets such as the US and Germany raised questions about the strength of an
export-led upturn.
The balance of manufacturers expecting sales to increase over the next year
was 38 per cent in the fourth quarter last year, compared with 47 per cent
in the third quarter. The balance is calculated by subtracting the
percentage of companies thinking sales will decline from the percentage
expecting a rise.
Similarly, the confidence balance for service companies declined to 38 per
cent in the fourth quarter last year from 42 per cent in the previous
quarter. Business confidence has, however, climbed significantly from the
first half of last year, when the recession was at an early stage.
Another brighter sign outlook emerged from the balance of 5 per cent of
manufacturers reporting increased orders for exports in the fourth quarter,
the first time since early 1990 that manufacturers seeing a rise in export
orders outnumbered those seeing a decline.
There were 'plenty of grounds for optimism' about a recovery, Mr Robin
Leigh-Pemberton, governor of the Bank of England, said last night in a
speech at Manchester Business School.
He said the stability given to sterling by the European exchange rate
mechanism should provide a platform for sustained growth in a
non-inflationary environment.
</TEXT>
