FT  23 JAN 92 / TSB tests photo credit-cards
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID BARCHARD
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
TSB, the sixth-largest UK banking group, is breaking ranks with the other
big lenders and introducing a trial scheme of putting photographs on credit
cards.
Mr Kenneth Baker, the home secretary, is leading government pressure on the
clearing banks to put photographs on credit cards to help combat fraud.
TSB will offer the chance of full-colour photographs to some of its
credit-card customers.
The big four clearers - Barclays, NatWest, Lloyds and Midland - say they are
not convinced that putting photographs on plastic payment cards would help
to reduce fraud. In private they claim that the government is trying to push
the banks to put photographs on cards as a substitute for a formal
identity-card scheme.
Royal Bank of Scotland has operated a trial scheme with black-and-white
photographs on cheque guarantee cards for nearly three months.
Selected customers holding the TSB Trustcard Visa card will be invited to
submit photographs for the trial, which will last a year.
About 15,000 card holders in the Brighton area will be included.
Photographs on credit cards have proved unexpectedly popular with customers.
Earlier this week Royal Bank said it was extending its trial scheme to
77,000 customers because of high demand from card holders.
The large banks are sceptical of the usefulness of photographs on cards,
saying they will not be more effective than existing security controls.
</TEXT>
