<HEADLINE>
FT  23 JAN 92 / Russian arms spending cuts 'almost end threat to US'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LIONEL BARBER, US Editor
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   WASHINGTON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
RUSSIA is drastically reducing military spending and poses virtually no
threat to the US, two top US intelligence officials told Congress yesterday.
The assessment by Mr Robert Gates, the new Central Intelligence Agency, and
General James Clapper, director of the Defence Intelligence Agency, could
stoke congressional pressure for even steeper cuts in the US defence budget.
President George Bush is expected - in his State of the Union address to
Congress next week - to propose cuts of up to Dollars 50bn in defence. These
would go well beyond current plans to reduce the US armed forces by 25 per
cent by 1994, though Democrats are calling for up to Dollars 100bn in
further reductions.
Gen Clapper told the Senate Armed Services committee that the Russian
republic appeared to have cut its military procurement in the first quarter
of this year by about 80 per cent, compared to past years.
Mr Gates noted the elimination of the SS-11 and SS-17 missiles, and of a
class of submarines, as well as the winding-down of the Blackjack strategic
bomber programme. For the first time in years, there was no new ballistic
missile programme under way.
The general said military procurement had affected 'virtually all categories
of equipment', with the former Soviet republics diverting resources to feed
and house troops. The military capabilities of Russia and the other
ex-Soviet successor states were in profound decline, he said.
However, the administration remains concerned about other threats posed by
the risk of nuclear proliferation and the abrasion between Russia and
Ukraine over control of the Red Army and the Black Sea fleet. Last year, Mr
Gates also referred to the threat of civil disorder caused by economic
reforms.
</TEXT>
