<HEADLINE>
FT  23 JAN 92 / Algeria wins a breathing space: Islamic party leader
arrested - Authorities maintain tight control
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT GRAHAM and FRANCIS GHILES
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   ALGIERS
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
A WEEK after returning from 28 years' exile to run Algeria's emergency
council of state, Mr Mohammed Boudiaf has for the moment headed off a threat
of serious civil strife.
By a skilful mix of concession and repression, and exploiting his untainted
political credentials, this 71-year-old veteran independence leader has won
an important breathing space. He has successfully countered the pressure
from the Islamic Salvation Front (FIS) which was denied certain victory in
the second round of the country's first multi-party elections that should
have been held on January 16.
Security forces last night arrested Mr Abdel Kader Hachani, the acting
leader of the FIS for inciting soldiers to desert the army.
The arrest was on the orders of Gen Khaled Nazzer, the minister of defence
and Algeria's military strong-man. Also detained for questioning were the
editor and deputy editor of Khabbar, the Arabic language newspaper
sympathetic to the FIS and the only one to have published the Front's
political statements.
The call to desert was issued over the weekend by the FIS ruling council,
the Majlis-es-Shura, which was addressed by Mr Hachani. Mr Hachani's arrest
was widely predicted and he had been telling colleagues he expected such a
reaction from the authorities.
The authorities this week again refused to release from jail Mr Abassi
Madani and Mr Ali ben Hadj, the two senior FIS leaders imprisoned since
June. The military-backed government has also continued to round up FIS
supporters. The FIS claims more than 500 have been arrested since the
military clampdown last week.
There have also been two reported instances of members of the security
forces being killed outside Algiers.
But the FIS has been careful to avoid a confrontation either by calling a
strike or by bringing its people on to the streets.
Within the past few days the army has returned to barracks, leaving only a
discreet presence of tanks outside key buildings. But it has retained a
tight cordon on roads leading to the capital at night.
The authorities have kept the FIS guessing whether or not the organisation
would be banned. They have also been careful to allow the press to speak
freely: however the bulk of the press has been inimical to the FIS's
declared aim of establishing an Islamic society.
Mr Boudiaf's return from exile in Morocco was negotiated by the six members
of the Higher Executive Committee. The latter was formed in the wake of
President Chadli Bendjedid's resignation on January 12 and is the real
decision-maker.
Before agreeing to lead Algeria in such dramatic circumstances after being
so long opposed to what he described as a military dictatorship, Mr Boudiaf
secretly visited Algiers. The conditions he set for his return remain
undisclosed. But it has been clear from the outset he intends to be more
than a mere puppet.
At the same time, the formation of the Council of State as a consultative
body composed of an astute mix of respected public figures unifying the
country's complex regional and religious activities, has signalled the
authorities' desire to operate by consensus.
In his only public statement, Mr Boudiaf warned the FIS that in a country
where Islam was the state religion no single group could claim it had a
monopoly. Equally significant, he was withering about the national
liberation front (FLN), which has dominated Algerian political life since
independence.
The other main lay party, the Social Front (FFS) headed by Mr Hocine Ait
Ahmed, the veteran Kabyle leader, has also sought dialogue with the FIS and
protested against the annulment. But Mr Ait Ahmed's opposition remains token
since he is opposed to imposition of full Islamic rule.
The FIS appears unable to decide whether to play for time and accept it must
operate under new rules or go underground. Against this background,
Algeria's new rulers believe they can count on a significant element in the
FIS vote having been a protest against corruption and the FLN's abuse of
power rather than a conviction to install Islamic fundamentalism. But this
protest vote, if that is what it was, will only be weaned from the FIS by
quick measures which address popular grievances of housing and employment.
</TEXT>
