FT  23 JAN 92 / Loyalist troops recapture Zaire radio
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By REUTER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   KINSHASA
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
ZAIRE'S national radio station in the capital Kinshasa was believed to be
back in government hands early this morning after rebel soldiers had seized
it and called on President Mobutu Sese Seko to resign, Reuter reports from
Kinshasa.
Ealier, gunfire had echoed through Kinshasa, witnesses said, as the mutinous
troops broadcast a call for the government of Prime Minister Nguza
Karl-i-Bond to step down.
Also yesterday, the European Community suspended all non-humanitarian aid to
Zaire in protest at the failure of the government to move towards a more
democratic system.
The soldiers, who seized the radio station at midnight, called on their
colleagues to stay in barracks and told the people not to riot.
The rebels appealed to the embassies of the US ,Belgium and France for
military help andsaid their action was due to the 'poverty and famine' in
the vast central African country.
Earlier in the day the main opposition party, Union for Democracy and Social
Progress said its co-chairmen, Mr Etienne Tshisekedi and Mr Frederic Kibassa
had been injured when presidential guards drove into a protest march in the
capital.
Supporters of the opposition alliance, Sacred Union, had clashed with troops
on Monday and Tuesday in protest at the suspension of a national conference
last Sunday aimed at guiding the country towards democracy.
The Sacred Union called a general strike starting today if the government
failed to revoke the suspension.
Kinshasa and other major cities were devastated by a wave of looting and
riots last September, triggered by unpaid troops. At least 250 people were
killed and some 20,000 expatriate workers were evacuated by French and
Belgian troops.
Earlier yesterday both Washington and Paris condemned Zaire for suspending
the national conference aimed at moving the country towards democracy.
