<HEADLINE>
FT  23 JAN 92 / Appointments: Kicking the habit
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
Alan Dunstan, who has spent 23 years at Abbey National, is kicking the habit
to join management consultants Oasis as head of the marketing and sales
management division.
Dunstan, who is 43, was sales director at Abbey for the last year, and
marketing director for the previous seven. He says that while the building
society had been through a vast upheaval during its metamorphosis into a
public company, he was worried that it was now entering a period of
stagnation - or worse. 'People were genuinely concerned about it becoming
another TSB.'
Unwilling to hang on for several years of potential frustration, he decided
to accept the approach from Oasis, an outfit which had impressed him three
years ago when he employed it to help Abbey develop its data base. He
reckons his experience with Abbey's shift from a product-to a
customer-driven business will have all sorts of applications among Oasis'
clients, which include other building societies as well as insurance
companies.
*****
Sir Alistair Frame is to become a public champion of Britain's manufacturing
sector, following his appointment as chairman of the National Manufacturing
Council of the CBI.
The Council was set up last year to help implement a strategy for
strengthening Britain's manufacturing base, following criticism of the CBI
for neglecting the needs of the manufacturing sector.
Sir Alistair, who is non-executive chairman of Wellcome, the pharmaceuticals
group, was until last year the chairman of RTZ Corporation. He is to become
chairman of British Steel in July and will head the CBI body for two years.
*****-
Salomon Brothers has appointed Steven Tye, currently head of Eurobond
trading, as head of the fixed income syndicate, replacing Simon Meadows who
left the company earlier this month.
