<HEADLINE>
FT  23 JAN 92 / UK Company News: Lower sales and earnings at enlarged
Borland Intl
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LOUISE KEHOE
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   SAN FRANCISCO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
BORLAND International, the US personal computer software company, reported a
decline in sales and flat earnings for its third quarter, following the
completion of its acquisition of Ashton-Tate, another US software company.
Results for the third quarter were reported on a 'pooling-of-interests'
basis, in which the results of the merged company are compared to the
accumulative results of both companies last year.
Revenues were Dollars 114.6m (Pounds 64m), a 6.6 per cent decrease compared
with Dollars 122.7m for the same period a year ago, the quarter ending in
December for Borland but ending in September for Ashton-Tate. Borland noted
that in its 1990 third quarter Ashton-Tate's sales were buoyed by the
introduction of a new product.
Net income was Dollars 7.5m, or 28 cents per share, compared with Dollars
6.8m last time. Borland took a Dollars 6m charge against third quarter
earnings in connection with the merger, bringing total pre-tax transaction
and restructuring charges over the past nine months to Dollars 116m. The
company also benefited from a Dollars 7m tax credit, also related to the
Ashton-Tate acquisition.
Revenues for the nine month period were Dollars 365.7m, up some 14 per cent
from Dollars 321.4m. The company reported a net loss of Dollars 83.5m, or
Dollars 3.42 per share, including restructuring and transaction charges,
compared with a net income of Dollars 2m or 8 cents per share, for the same
period a year ago.
