FT  23 JAN 92 / Loss of 1,105 mine jobs is confirmed
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JULIET SYCHRAVA
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
BRITISH COAL yesterday confirmed it will cut 1,105 jobs at four pits in its
Selby group of mines in West Yorkshire including its flagship Selby complex,
a costly development the size of the Isle of Wight.
More than 200 jobs are to go at Whitemoor, one of seven pits in the Selby
complex itself. Another 150 will be eliminated at Sharlston, near Wakefield
while 410 and 350 redundancies, respectively, are earmarked at Kellingley
and Prince of Wales, both near Pontefract.
Confirmation of the cuts came as British Coal announced a further 30 to 40
job losses at Kiveton Colliery in its South Yorkshire group.
The announcement fuelled speculation that the company is attempting to
reduce manpower and improve productivity in readiness for privatisation if
the Conservatives win the next election.
British Coal said the cuts were necessary if the mines were to bring down
costs sufficiently to sell to the newly privatised electricity industry at
competitive prices after March 1993, when government-backed contracts run
out.
The company may also be trying to cut the volume of output, according to the
newsletter Coal UK, published today. In spite of 12 pit closures this year
the company still has more coal than it can sell to the generators, the
newsletter says, not the least as a result of improvements in productivity.
But Mr Alan Houghton, Selby group director, said the job losses would not
result in output reductions. He said they were aimed at ensuring that the
pits were 'physically and financially strong'.
There is no sign so far that the four Selby pits affected by the job cuts
face closure.
Kellingley is one of the 14 mines picked by NM Rothschild, the government
advisers on coal privatisation in their controversial report leaked last
year, as profitable enough for a sell-off. Mr Frank Dobson, the shadow
energy secretary, said yesterday: 'It makes phenomenal profits.'
The other three mines, which were not chosen by Rothschild, are believed by
industry observers to be either loss-making or close to breaking even.
Three of the pits in the Selby group - Riccall, Wistow, and Stillingfleet -
have frequently broken productivity records, but both Whitemoor and North
Selby, the most recent mine to open, have suffered geological problems which
have sometimes halted or seriously slowed down production.
Mr Ken Capstick, vice-chairman of the National Union of Mineworkers in
Yorkshire, said that he believed any problems the pits had were surmountable
and blamed the cuts on the government's decision that British Coal must
compete in the international market.
British Coal said all redundancies would be voluntary but Mr Dobson said the
company was able to achieve thisonly by offering miners a top-up payment of
up to Pounds 10,000 if they took redundancy before the end of March.
</TEXT>
