<HEADLINE>
FT  22 JAN 92 / World Stock Markets (America): Profit-taking and stock
rotation dominate trade
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PATRICK HARVERSON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Wall Street
PROFIT-TAKING and switching between sectors continued to exact a toll on US
stock markets yesterday, writes Patrick Harverson in New York.
The Dow Jones Industrial Average finished 30.64 off at 3,223.39 and the more
broadly based Standard &amp; Poor's 500 lost 3.72 to 412.64. Over-the-counter
stocks also succumbed to profit-taking, the Nasdaq composite index falling
14.51 to 604.87. New York SE turnover was 219m shares and declines led rises
by 1,186 to 569.
There has been no discernible shift in underlying market sentiment in recent
days, and the dominant trends of the past week - profit-taking and
rotational trading - were still in place yesterday.
The two trends are linked; investors take profits in sectors which look
overbought, and switch into sectors which look cheap and offer potential for
bigger gains. Although the headline numbers show a decline, little money
actually leaves the market.
Among individual stocks, fourth-quarter figures proved the biggest influence
on price movements. Wells Fargo dropped Dollars 2 3/8 to Dollars 65 on
announcing a quarterly loss of Dollars 231m after making Dollars 700m of
loan-loss provisions, made primarily to cover real estate losses.
The two other big California-based banks, BankAmerica and Security Pacific
(which also reported a final quarter loss) slipped Dollars 1 1/4 to Dollars
38 7/8 and Dollars  7/8 to Dollars 32 5/8 respectively.
United Technologies dipped Dollars 1 1/4 to Dollars 54 after unveiling big
fourth-quarter losses, taken after a Dollars 1.275bn restructuring charge
and a Dollars 256m charge for increases in environmental reserves, both of
which were higher than expectations. The group announced plans to shed
13,900 jobs and close down or consolidate 100 facilities.
Coca-Cola Enterprises, the largest bottling company for the big soft drinks
group, receded Dollars  3/4 to Dollars 14 3/8 after the company said it
would make a Dollars 152m restructuring charge and a Dollars 15m addition to
its insurance reserve during the fourth quarter. The charge, and revised
1991 earnings, mean that Coca-Cola Enterprises will announce a full-year
loss of about 79 cents a share when it unveils its results next month.
Revived rumours of possible bid interest from Jacuzzi, a Hanson subsidiary,
lifted Eljer Industries Dollars  7/8 to Dollars 11 5/8 . The stock was also
buoyed by speculation that the company may be close to negotiating more
favourable loan covenant settlements with its banks.
Leading over-the-counter stocks suffered at the hands of the profit-takers.
Apple retreated Dollars 2 7/8 to Dollars 61 1/8 , Microsoft gave up Dollars
3 1/8 to Dollars 119 3/8 , Amgen slipped Dollars 1 1/4 to Dollars 66 1/4 and
Borland International, which reported a 10 per cent gain in fiscal
third-quarter net income, fell Dollars 1 1/2 to Dollars 70 1/2 .
Canada
TORONTO stocks suffered a setback and ended at the day's worst on
profit-taking and nervousness over Ontario Premier Bob Rae's speech
scheduled for last night. Banks fell sharply on fears that Mr Rae would
somehow raise taxes for financial institutions.
The composite index surrendered 35.2 at 3,620.4. Declines led advances by
356 to 274 after volume of 31.7m shares (30.5m).
Alcan fell CDollars 1 1/8 to CDollars 24 1/4 . Traders said Kidder Peabody
downgraded the company's shares to a hold from a buy. On Monday Alcan
reported a 1991 loss of 25 cents per share.
</TEXT>
