<HEADLINE>
FT  22 JAN 92 / World Stock Markets (Europe): Continent gets support from
firmer bond prices
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By Our Markets Staff
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
FIRMER bond markets in the D-Mark bloc supported some bourses yesterday,
writes Our Markets Staff.
FRANKFURT met profit-taking as the DAX index tested 1,700. It reached an
intraday high of 1,698.14 but closed more soberly at 1,685.29, up 8.12,
after a gain of 10.14 to 687.20 for the FAZ at midsession.
Volume climbed from DM6.5bn to DM9.5bn. In the early going the stock market
was supported by firmer prices in the German bond market, where the
Bundesbank's average bond yield dropped another 8 basis points to 8.03 per
cent. Banks saw the benefit, Commerzbank rising DM3.50 to DM261 and Dresdner
by DM5.50 to DM354.
There was no outcome, during the session or in the post-bourse, to the pay
talks between the steel industry and its employees. The sector weakened
after its recent gains, Klockner-Werke dropping DM3 to DM116; other sectors
on the move included retailers on the downgrade, and constructions improving
with Bilfinger &amp; Berger DM20 higher at DM970.
PARIS came off the day's high but still closed firmer as dealers started to
square positions ahead of the liquidation of the January account tomorrow.
The CAC 40 index went as high as 1,878.27 before closing at 1,867.91, up
2.06, in turnover estimated between FFr2.6-2.7bn after Monday's FFr2.7bn.
BSN dropped FFr45 or 3.9 per cent to FFr1,109 with 229,960 shares traded, as
the market took the view that a bid from the Agnelli family was unlikely
before the Cob made a decision on the recent sale of Perrier treasury stock
to Saint Louis, an Agnelli ally.
Thomson-CSF lost FFr6 or 3.8 per cent to FFr150.50 with 223,100 shares
traded on reports that the government was considering merging the company
with Aerospatiale, the state-owned aircraft group. Analysts said the Airbus
crash on Monday night also weighed on Thomson, which is partially
responsible for the avionics in the aircraft.
MILAN fell for the second day as investors started an uneasy vigil for
Fiat's 1991 operating profit details. The letter to shareholders had been
expected today, but analysts said its release had been delayed until January
28. The Comit index, which failed to break through 550 during the recent
rally, lost 6.29 to 539.96 in provisional turnover of L120bn after Monday's
L103.5bn.
Among industrials, Fiat fell L164 to L5,175 and lost another L15 in
after-hours trading. Pirelli dropped L42 or 3.4 per cent to L1,180 following
Monday's marathon extraordinary meeting during which shareholders accused
the management of mismanagement and withholding information in a failed bid
for Germany's Continental. However, the L518.6bn capital increase was
approved.
ZURICH mirrored Frankfurt with a firmer bond market. The all-share SPI index
added 5.1 to 1,110.4 after peaking earlier at 1,113.6.
Saurer, the textile machinery and metallurgy group, climbed SFr200 to
SFr1,850 ahead of a press conference tomorrow. EMS-Chemie bearers added
SFr80 to SFr5,050 after the company said that it planned to split its
registered and bearer shares to reduce the weight of the share prices.
AMSTERDAM, inspired by a firm bond market and new year investment from
abroad, closed almost one per cent firmer. The CBS Tendency Index closed up
1.3 at 121.1. Philips, the electronics group, was 70 cents firmer at Fl
32.90 while the food group CSM was also in demand, rising 50 cents to Fl
89.00.
MADRID ended flat in moderate trading, despite a strong opening, with the
general index down 0.02 at 252.62. Turnover rose to Pta18.5bn from Pta15bn.
Repsol closed Pta30 higher at Pta2,825 with a large block order boosting
volume. Some utility issues showed strong gains: Catalana de Gas put on
Pta110 to Pta5,970 while Fecsa advanced Pta9 to Pta713. Insurers Mapfre lost
Pta85 to Pta4,805, and Union Fenix fell Pta95 to Pta4,555.
STOCKHOLM fell in active trade as an overnight decline on Wall Street
triggered profit-taking after four days of gains. The Affarsvarlden General
Index closed down 11.0 at 978.2. Volume remained heavy at SKr498m. The
insurance sector fell 2.2 per cent and forestry, a strong performer in the
past three sessions, slipped 2.0 per cent.
OSLO lost 1.4 per cent on profit-taking, the all-share index closing 6.50
lower at 454.17 in active turnover of NKr341m. Oils and oils-associated
stocks went both ways, as Norsk Hydro fell NKr3 to NKr158 while Saga
Petroleum free shares ended NKr3 higher at NKr99.
BRUSSELS focused on Gechem and firm Acec-UM as it closed 1.7 per cent higher
on the first day of the new forward account. The Bel-20 index closed up
19.88 at 1,181.69 in high turnover of BFr1.22bn.
