<HEADLINE>
FT  22 JAN 92 / International Capital Markets: Japanese brokerage
reorganisation
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By EMIKO TERAZONO
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
DAIWA Securities, a leading Japanese brokerage, yesterday announced it would
transfer 200 head office personnel to domestic branches, writes Emiko
Terazono.
The move reflects the company's need to boost branch level sales
commissions, which have declined sharply due to the sluggish stock market.
Japanese brokerages have been hard hit by the low trading volumes in the
equity market stemming from deteriorating investor confidence.
While smaller brokers, which rely heavily on stock broking commissions and
have been hit by the faltering market, have been announcing shifts of head
office employees to sales branches, Daiwa will be the first of the big four
brokerages - which also include Nomura, Nikko and Yamaichi - to implement
such changes. Yamaichi Securities also said it was considering a
reorganisation of employees at the end of next month.
The move also represents a change in business strategy of the leading
brokerages. The big four have been pressured to allow more autonomy to the
branches, as previous sales methods which involved the head office issuing
stock recommendations through branch networks have been criticised for
distorting share prices and, in some cases, price manipulation. Now the
branches are expected to operate more independently, tailoring investment
advice to local conditions and local customers' needs.
</TEXT>
