<HEADLINE>
FT  22 JAN 92 / Cable and Wireless talks collapse
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By HUGO DIXON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
NEGOTIATIONS between American Telephone and Telegraph and Cable and Wireless
over forming a global alliance between the two telecommunications groups
have broken down because of political concern in the run-up to the UK
general election.
A central element of the alliance would have involved the US group buying a
minority stake in Mercury Communications, C and W's UK subsidiary.
AT&amp;T is understood to have been concerned that it could have become a pawn
in a much bigger game between the Labour and Conservative parties in the
tense pre-election period.
Talks between the two groups may start again after the election. This is
likely to depend partly on who wins - in particular, whether a Labour
government would change telecommunications policy - and partly on what
alternative alliances the groups pursue in the interim.
C and W's share price closed down 17p at 589p last night as the stock market
sensed that a deal had fallen through. Last week, when the market believed
an agreement was imminent, the price peaked at 632p.
Political worries are not the only reason that a deal, which has been the
subject of talks since last September, has not been concluded.
C and W, which is chaired by Lord Young, wants to collaborate throughout
Europe, not just on Mercury. But it is not clear whether AT&amp;T, which is
chaired by Mr Bob Allen, is willing to negotiate such a broad deal or would
prefer different partners in different geographical markets.
During the past six months, the international telecommunications industry
has been in a frenzy of deal-making, as what were once national monopolies
try to turn themselves into globally competitive operators.
Failure to conclude a deal now between AT&amp;T and C and W may mean that other
partners look more attractive to both groups after the election.
C and W has in the past considered taking a stake in Sprint, the third
largest US long-distance telecommunications carrier. It also planned to
develop its own presence in the US market by acquiring TRT/FTC, the fourth
largest carrier, but pulled out of this deal last November.
AT&amp;T has held talks with a number of European companies, including Germany's
Bundespost Telekom and France Telecom.
Mr Allen's ambition is that AT&amp;T will earn half its revenue outside the US
by the year 2000, compared with less than a quarter today.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 17
</PAGE>
